<p>What are venture capitalists looking for? If you are a startup entrepreneur looking for funding, it&#8217;s always a good idea to know what investment themes a VC is interested and tailor your pitch to those themes. Yesterday morning, I saw presentations from three venture firms?<a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/union-square-ventures">Union Square Ventures</a>, <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/dfj-gotham-ventures">DFJ Gotham Ventures</a>, and <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/first-round-capital">First Round Capital</a>?at an event hosted by the <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.mediakitchen.tv/">Media Kitchen</a>. Each of the presenters outlined some of the themes their venture firms are trying to ride. They all boil down to structural change in one form or another. </p>
