</div><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Techcrunch/~4/319396377" height="1" width="1"/>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1214366756;}i:25;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:24:"Vegetable are delicious.";s:4:"link";s:50:"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~3/315928851/";s:11:"description";s:299:"I&#8217;ve been thinking a lot about my last post and I&#8217;ve come to a new conclusion. The optimism and defeat I feel are my own which I am projecting onto Toronto and Hamilton. There is just as much opportunity in Hamilton as Toronto, I just have to go out and look for it.
In other news, [...]";s:4:"guid";s:22:"http://eimaj.net/?p=17";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Thu, 19 Jun 2008 21:01:01 PDT";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2194:"<p><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://eimaj.net/wp-content/uploads/2008/06/451px-arcimboldo_vegetables.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-18" title="arcimboldo_vegetables" src="http://eimaj.net/wp-content/uploads/2008/06/451px-arcimboldo_vegetables-250x332.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="332"/></a>I&#8217;ve been thinking a lot about my <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://eimaj.net/comparing-peas-to-carrots/">last post</a> and I&#8217;ve come to a new conclusion. The optimism and defeat I feel are my own which I am projecting onto Toronto and Hamilton. There is just as much opportunity in Hamilton as Toronto, I just have to go out and look for it.</p>
<p>In other news, and to make the title of this post a little more relevant, I actually do love vegetables. Currently I&#8217;ve been getting fresh, seasonal, locally produced vegetables every week from <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.planborganicfarms.ca/">Plan B Organic Farms</a>. The have a pick up location in the backyard at my work.</p>
<p>Plan B participates in a program called <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/">Community Shared Agriculture (CSA)</a>. To quote the Plan B site: &#8220;Community Shared Agriculture (CSA) is a system of growing and distributing organic produce that restores the link between the farmers and city dwellers.&#8221;</p>
<p>These programs reduce the transportation costs and guarantee revenue for local farm and provide the consumer with fresh, seasonal, organic produce. And because you are buying local, it helps support and strengthen your local economy. There are program like this all over the province.</p>
<p>If you would be interested in something like this check out the following lists to see what&#8217;s available in your area. The <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/">CSA Ontario website</a> has a list by <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/farms%20cities.htm">city</a> or by <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/CSA%20farmers.htm">county</a>.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~4/315928851" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:7:"summary";s:299:"I&#8217;ve been thinking a lot about my last post and I&#8217;ve come to a new conclusion. The optimism and defeat I feel are my own which I am projecting onto Toronto and Hamilton. There is just as much opportunity in Hamilton as Toronto, I just have to go out and look for it.
In other news, [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:2194:"<p><a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://eimaj.net/wp-content/uploads/2008/06/451px-arcimboldo_vegetables.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-18" title="arcimboldo_vegetables" src="http://eimaj.net/wp-content/uploads/2008/06/451px-arcimboldo_vegetables-250x332.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="332"/></a>I&#8217;ve been thinking a lot about my <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://eimaj.net/comparing-peas-to-carrots/">last post</a> and I&#8217;ve come to a new conclusion. The optimism and defeat I feel are my own which I am projecting onto Toronto and Hamilton. There is just as much opportunity in Hamilton as Toronto, I just have to go out and look for it.</p>
<p>In other news, and to make the title of this post a little more relevant, I actually do love vegetables. Currently I&#8217;ve been getting fresh, seasonal, locally produced vegetables every week from <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.planborganicfarms.ca/">Plan B Organic Farms</a>. The have a pick up location in the backyard at my work.</p>
<p>Plan B participates in a program called <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/">Community Shared Agriculture (CSA)</a>. To quote the Plan B site: &#8220;Community Shared Agriculture (CSA) is a system of growing and distributing organic produce that restores the link between the farmers and city dwellers.&#8221;</p>
<p>These programs reduce the transportation costs and guarantee revenue for local farm and provide the consumer with fresh, seasonal, organic produce. And because you are buying local, it helps support and strengthen your local economy. There are program like this all over the province.</p>
<p>If you would be interested in something like this check out the following lists to see what&#8217;s available in your area. The <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/">CSA Ontario website</a> has a list by <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/farms%20cities.htm">city</a> or by <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://csafarms.ca/CSA%20farmers.htm">county</a>.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~4/315928851" height="1" width="1"/>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1213934461;}i:26;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:26:"Comparing peas to carrots.";s:4:"link";s:50:"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~3/313495521/";s:11:"description";s:265:"For the past two years I lived in Toronto. As poor as I was, I loved it. There is always something going on, and it was usually easy to find someone to talk to. About a month ago I moved to Hamilton for a job with Social Media Group. I love it. The people are [...]";s:4:"guid";s:22:"http://eimaj.net/?p=14";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Mon, 16 Jun 2008 20:19:23 PDT";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1566:"<p>For the past two years I lived in Toronto. As poor as I was, I loved it. There is always something going on, and it was usually easy to find someone to talk to. About a month ago I moved to Hamilton for a job with <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://socialmediagroup.ca/">Social Media Group</a>. I love it. The people are great, the projects are interesting and challenging and for the first time ever I feel like I have a job. That looks weird when I type it, but it makes sense to me. I&#8217;ve had jobs, but not a job&#8230;</p>
<p>Anyhow. Aside from the job, I&#8217;ve been having trouble adapting to Hamilton. It&#8217;s only been a month though, so I&#8217;m not concerned. I think part of the problem is I constantly find myself comparing Hamilton to Toronto and for the past month I&#8217;ve been trying to find one, underlying difference. (Aside: I don&#8217; think there is just one, but I like to over-simplify things sometimes.) This weekend in Toronto I came to a rather abrupt conclusion that I kind of think fits. Feel free to let me know how BS you think it is.</p>
<p>While wandering around Toronto I am met with a sense of optimism that I have never felt in Hamilton. Just an underlying feeling in the city. In Hamilton I feel a sense of defeat. This is by no means a solid conclusion based on fact. It&#8217;s something I felt in my gut. I&#8217;ll think about it more, but I just wanted to put it out there, maybe see what other people think.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~4/313495521" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:7:"summary";s:265:"For the past two years I lived in Toronto. As poor as I was, I loved it. There is always something going on, and it was usually easy to find someone to talk to. About a month ago I moved to Hamilton for a job with Social Media Group. I love it. The people are [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:1566:"<p>For the past two years I lived in Toronto. As poor as I was, I loved it. There is always something going on, and it was usually easy to find someone to talk to. About a month ago I moved to Hamilton for a job with <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://socialmediagroup.ca/">Social Media Group</a>. I love it. The people are great, the projects are interesting and challenging and for the first time ever I feel like I have a job. That looks weird when I type it, but it makes sense to me. I&#8217;ve had jobs, but not a job&#8230;</p>
<p>Anyhow. Aside from the job, I&#8217;ve been having trouble adapting to Hamilton. It&#8217;s only been a month though, so I&#8217;m not concerned. I think part of the problem is I constantly find myself comparing Hamilton to Toronto and for the past month I&#8217;ve been trying to find one, underlying difference. (Aside: I don&#8217; think there is just one, but I like to over-simplify things sometimes.) This weekend in Toronto I came to a rather abrupt conclusion that I kind of think fits. Feel free to let me know how BS you think it is.</p>
<p>While wandering around Toronto I am met with a sense of optimism that I have never felt in Hamilton. Just an underlying feeling in the city. In Hamilton I feel a sense of defeat. This is by no means a solid conclusion based on fact. It&#8217;s something I felt in my gut. I&#8217;ll think about it more, but I just wanted to put it out there, maybe see what other people think.</p>
<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~4/313495521" height="1" width="1"/>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1213672763;}i:27;a:9:{s:5:"title";s:25:"James St. North Art Crawl";s:4:"link";s:50:"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/eimaj/~3/313495522/";s:11:"description";s:303:"I met up with some friends to visit the James St. N. Art Crawl last night. There was a crazy storm which delayed our departure, but we made it to a few shows before the galleries closed. One in particular was pretty cool.
It was a solo exhibition at Atomica Tattoo called One Liners (pun intended) [...]";s:4:"guid";s:22:"http://eimaj.net/?p=13";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Sat, 14 Jun 2008 06:00:24 PDT";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1529:"<p>I met up with some friends to visit the <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.raisethehammer.org/wots.asp?id=201">James St. N. Art Crawl</a> last night. There was a crazy storm which delayed our departure, but we made it to a few shows before the galleries closed. One in particular was pretty cool.</p>
<p>It was a solo exhibition at <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://atomicatattoo.com/">Atomica Tattoo</a> called <em>One Liners</em> (pun intended) and featured the work of <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://etchmaster.blogspot.com/">Kyle Fleming</a>. Fleming creates his drawings using an Etch-A-Sketch&#8230; Remember those red screens with the two dials? Well, this guy draws with them. Check out his <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/user/mcetcher">videos here</a>.</p>
<p>The stuff is crazy. He has made them permanent (and marketable &#8212; always a challenge for art) by removing the powder and crazy-gluing the dials in place. With his pop-culture subject, he wasn&#8217;t having trouble selling them either, even at 900$ each. He also had signed and numbered limited edition photographs available for sale. Warhol would be proud.</p>
<p>All in all is was excellent to talk art again. I missed it.</p>
<p><iframe class="embeddedvideo" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="425" height="344" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/NXsAQfzew1M&amp;hl=en"></iframe></p> 
