It was a solo exhibition at Atomica Tattoo called One Liners (pun intended) [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:1529:"<p>I met up with some friends to visit the <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.raisethehammer.org/wots.asp?id=201">James St. N. Art Crawl</a> last night. There was a crazy storm which delayed our departure, but we made it to a few shows before the galleries closed. One in particular was pretty cool.</p>
<p>It was a solo exhibition at <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://atomicatattoo.com/">Atomica Tattoo</a> called <em>One Liners</em> (pun intended) and featured the work of <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://etchmaster.blogspot.com/">Kyle Fleming</a>. Fleming creates his drawings using an Etch-A-Sketch&#8230; Remember those red screens with the two dials? Well, this guy draws with them. Check out his <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.youtube.com/user/mcetcher">videos here</a>.</p>
<p>The stuff is crazy. He has made them permanent (and marketable &#8212; always a challenge for art) by removing the powder and crazy-gluing the dials in place. With his pop-culture subject, he wasn&#8217;t having trouble selling them either, even at 900$ each. He also had signed and numbered limited edition photographs available for sale. Warhol would be proud.</p>
<p>All in all is was excellent to talk art again. I missed it.</p>
