</div><img src="http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~4/320574363" height="1" width="1"/>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1214490900;}i:40;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:85:"Signal Jacket for Cyclists Gets Instructable: Your Arms Will be Happy [Leah Buechley]";s:4:"link";s:121:"http://feeds.gawker.com/~r/gizmodo/full/~3/320564856/signal-jacket-for-cyclists-gets-instructable-your-arms-will-be-happy";s:11:"description";s:2478:"<p><img src="http://gizmodo.com/assets/images/gizmodo/2008/06/cyclistjacket.jpg" width="494" height="428" style="display:block;float:none;display:block;float:none;"/>Back in March we showed <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://gizmodo.com/367988/signal-jacket-for-cyclists">Leah Buechley's</a> neat signaling jacket for cyclists, the one that has LED turn-indicators on the back. Not much info was available on it at the time, save for the fact it used an Arduino Lilypad controller. But now Leah's posted a detailed <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.instructables.com/">Instructable</a> for the jacket, including handy things like a shopping list for materials and tools, so you could easily make your own. One thing we didn't know: there's a single LED on each cuff, confirming your turn signs are showing on the back. Good idea that&mdash;saving you from veering into the path of a juggernaut that didn't know what you were up to. [<a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.instructables.com/id/turn-signal-biking-jacket/">Instructables</a> via <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://www.talk2myshirt.com/blog/archives/530">Talk2myshirt</a>]</p> <br style="clear:both;"/> <img alt="" style="border:0;height:1px;width:1px;" border="0" src="http://www.pheedo.com/img.phdo?i=a94de5059eed96502850d83785b2ea3d" height="1" width="1"/> 
